solution_md:
Let $A_j = \{i: 2^{j-1} \le a_i < 2^j\}, j = 1, 2, \dots, 11$. The $A_j$ form a partition of the index set $\{1, 2, \dots, n\}$.

Note that, for every $j$ in the range 1 through 11, if $A_j$ is non-empty, then
$$
\begin{aligned}
\sum_{i \in A_j} \frac{1}{a_i} (a_1 + a_2 + \dots + a_i) &= \sum_{i \in A_j} \left( \frac{a_1 + a_2 + \dots + a_{i-1}}{a_i} + 1 \right) \\
&> \sum_{k=0}^{|A_j|-1} \frac{k \cdot 2^{j-1}}{2^j} + |A_j| = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^{|A_j|-1} k + |A_j| \\
&= \frac{1}{4} |A_j|(|A_j| - 1) + |A_j| = \frac{1}{4} |A_j|(|A_j| + 3);
\end{aligned}
$$

As the $A_j$ form a partition of the index set $\{1, 2, \dots, n\}$ and at least one $A_j$ is non-empty,
$$
\begin{aligned}
\sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{1}{a_i} (a_1 + a_2 + \dots + a_i) &= \sum_{j=1}^{11} \sum_{i \in A_j} \frac{1}{a_i} (a_1 + a_2 + \dots + a_i) \\
&> \frac{1}{4} \sum_{j=1}^{11} |A_j|(|A_j| + 3) = \frac{1}{4} \left( \sum_{j=1}^{11} |A_j|^2 + 3n \right) \\
&\ge \frac{1}{4} \left( \frac{n^2}{11} + 3n \right) = \frac{1}{44} n(n + 33), \text{ by Cauchy-Schwarz.}
\end{aligned}

problem_md:
Let $ABCD$ be a square, $M$ be the midpoint of the side $AD$, $T$ be the common point of the lines $BM$ and $CD$, and $CP \perp BM$, $P \in MB$. The perpendicular line from $A$ to $AP$ intersects the line $BM$ in $Q$. Prove that:

